    <section id="introduction" class="reveal">
  <p>Up to one in four people who suffer a hip fracture are dead within a year. Not disabled. Not diminished. Dead. Another 40% of survivors cannot walk independently, and a third end up either fully dependent or in a nursing home. This is not a rare complication of an uncommon disease — more than 10 million hip fractures occur globally each year in people aged 55 and older, a figure drawn from the 2019 Global Burden of Disease analysis across 204 countries, and one projected to nearly double by 2050. The numbers for men are worse than anyone talks about: a 310% projected increase compared to 1990 rates. For women, 240%.</p>
  <p>Now consider the institutional response to this crisis. Clinicians, guided by decades of cautious exercise guidelines, have been steering the most at-risk patients toward gentle movement — walking programs, low-intensity aerobics, the kind of activity that feels responsible and produces, in terms of bone adaptation, almost nothing. Meanwhile, the intervention with the strongest evidence base — heavy, supervised, high-intensity resistance training — sits largely outside standard clinical practice, not because the evidence is weak, but because the medical establishment decided, with the best of intentions, that old bones and heavy barbells were a dangerous combination.</p>
  <p>The LIFTMOR trial authors put it with a precision that should embarrass every guideline committee that has met since 2018: "Safety concerns alone have prevented the well-recognised preferential response of bone tissue to high-intensity loads from being applied to those who stand to benefit the most." That sentence is not a research suggestion. It is a verdict.</p>
</section>

<section id="the-arithmetic-of-small-numbers" class="reveal">
  <h2>The Arithmetic of Small Numbers</h2>
  <p>The BMD numbers produced by resistance training look modest on paper. A meta-analysis published in Healthcare (MDPI, 2022) analyzing seven RCTs involving 370 older adults found that resistance training protocols at 70–90% of one-rep max produced improvements of +0.64% at the hip and +0.62% at the lumbar spine, while control groups declined. Less than one percent. Easy to dismiss.</p>
  <p>Don't.</p>
  <p>A 1% increase in spine BMD reduces fracture risk by approximately 8%. A 5% increase in BMD raises bone strength by roughly 65%. These relationships, cited in a 2019 PMC review of exercise interventions, mean that the modest absolute numbers on a DXA scan translate into something that looks very different in a fracture ward. The gains are not dramatic. The clinical implications are. The difference between a bone that fractures and one that doesn't is not measured in dramatic density shifts — it is measured in the kind of incremental structural reinforcement that resistance training, uniquely among non-pharmacological interventions, is capable of producing at the specific anatomical sites that kill people: the femoral neck and the lumbar vertebrae.</p>
  <p>High-velocity and high-intensity resistance training produces BMD improvements of 0.9% to 5.4% at the lumbar spine, total hip, and femoral neck, according to a 2024 systematic review in Bone examining 25 studies including 8 RCTs with 1,203 participants. At the upper end of that range, you are not talking about a marginal intervention. You are talking about a structural transformation that no pill currently on the market reliably replicates without its own risk profile.</p>
</section>

<aside class="pull-quote reveal"><p>"Safety concerns alone have prevented the well-recognised preferential response of bone tissue to high-intensity loads from being applied to those who stand to benefit the most." — Watson et al., LIFTMOR trial authors</p></aside>

<section id="liftmor-the-rebuke" class="reveal">
  <h2>LIFTMOR: The Rebuke</h2>
  <p>The LIFTMOR randomized controlled trial, published in the Journal of Bone and Mineral Research in 2018, is the study that should have changed everything. It didn't. That failure is the story.</p>
  <p>Watson and colleagues randomized 101 postmenopausal women with low bone mass — mean age 65, the exact population that clinical guidelines treat as too fragile for high-intensity loading — to either twice-weekly supervised high-intensity resistance and impact training at greater than 85% of one-rep maximum, or a low-intensity home exercise control. The training protocol included deadlifts, back squats, and overhead presses. The exercises that physiatrists and general practitioners reflexively warn their osteopenic patients away from.</p>
  <p>After eight months: femoral neck BMD improved by +0.3% in the high-intensity group while controls lost 2.5%. Lumbar spine BMD improved by +1.6% in the high-intensity group while controls lost 1.7%. Compliance exceeded 87%. Zero fractures occurred in the high-intensity group.</p>
  <p>Read that again. The women doing heavy deadlifts had better bone outcomes and fewer fractures than the women doing gentle home exercise. The intervention the guidelines were designed to protect patients from turned out to be safer and more effective than the intervention the guidelines were steering them toward.</p>
  <p>This is not a pilot study. It is not preliminary data. It is a well-designed RCT with a clinically relevant population, a meaningful comparator, and an effect size that dwarfs what most pharmaceutical interventions produce in equivalent timeframes. The 3.2 percentage point divergence in femoral neck BMD between groups over eight months — the high-intensity group gaining while controls lost — represents the kind of between-group difference that, in a drug trial, would generate a press release and a fast-track FDA review.</p>
</section>

